1.  TYPE OF DATA

1.1  Parameter/Measurement. Surface air temperature

1.2  Unit of Measurement.  Degrees Centigrade

1.3  Data Source. The mean monthly values of surface air temperature have
been taken from the archives of climate information available on magnetic
tape.  The sources of this information include the reference books "World
Weather Records", "Monthly Climatic Data for the World" and "Meteorological
Data for Individual Years over the Northern Hemisphere Excluding the USSR",
and are supplemented with information from various national publications.
                                                                                
1.4  Data Set Identification. The zonal temperature data reside within NCDS
as VGL-TMP-DEV_MONTHLY, VGL-TMP-DEV_SEASONAL, VGL-TMP-DEV_ANNUAL.  The
station data are available through NCDS as VGL-TMP-MON_NORTH-STATN and
VGL_TMP_MON_SOUTH-STATN.  VGL is an acronym for the data set producers:
Vinnikov, Groisman, and Lugina.

                                                                                
2.  SPATIAL CHARACTERISTICS                                                     
                                                                                
2.1  Spatial Coverage.  Based on statistically optimum spatial averaging of
meteorological fields developed by Gandin (1965), and Kagin (1979), 301
stations in the Northern Hemisphere, and 265 stations in the Southern
Hemisphere were used for determining the mean temperatures.
                                                                                
2.2  Spatial Resolution. 30 degree latitudinal zones (6) 
                                                                                
                      90 deg N -60 deg N                                        
                      60 deg N -30 deg N                                        
                      30 deg N - 0 deg                                          
                      0  deg   -30 deg S                                        
                      30 deg S -60 deg S                                        
                      60 deg S -90 deg S                                        
                                                                                
For the 60 - 90 degree South zone, data are available only after 1957. As a
result, the estimate that is calculated for the 0 - 60 degree South zone is
used to characterize the entire Southern Hemisphere for the period 1881 to
1990.

                                                                                
3.  TEMPORAL CHARACTERISTICS                                                    
                                                                                
3.1  Temporal Coverage.  These data cover the time period 1881-1990.            
                                                                                
3.2  Temporal Resolution.  Monthly                                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
