5.  DATA PROCESSING SEQUENCE                                                    
                                                                                
5.1  Processing Steps and Data Sets.  Statistically optimum spatial
averaging of the time series of the mean surface air temperature anomalies
was employed.  More precise information concerning the exact steps and data
can be obtained from Vinnikov et al. (1987, 1990) and Groisman and Lugina
(1985).
                                                                                
5.2  Derivation Techniques/Algorithms.  All the data used have been
thoroughly checked for homogeneity of observational series,
representativeness, and presence of random errors.  The inferences about
series homogeneity and proposals for their correction from Jones et al.
(1985, 1986) have been also taken into account.  As a result, the following
networks have been selected:  301 stations are used to estimate the mean
temperature of the Northern Hemisphere and 265 stations are used to
estimate the mean temperature of the Southern Hemisphere.  For the 1881 -
1990 period, the Northern Hemisphere network proved to be sufficient to
provide an accurate spatial averaging (Vinnikov et al. 1987).  In the last
quarter of the 19th century, the Southern Hemisphere network of stations is
very sparse.  The increase in the number of stations in different parts of
the hemisphere between 1881 - 1941 is documented as follows:
                                                                                
                                 Australia    Total number                      
Year    Africa    S. America    and Oceania    of stations                      
_____________________________________________________________                   
                                                                                
1881      1            2             6               9                          
1901     12           13            12              37                          
1921     17           22            23              62                          
1941     40           54            35             129                          
All                                                                             
Years    80          100            85             265                          
____________________________________________________________                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
5.3  Special Corrections/Adjustments.  A homogenous time series has been
created for the following locations from data of neighboring stations using
an overlapping period of data.  These stations include:  Honolulu, Hawaii;
Lihue, Hawaii; Tarawa, Kilibatchee; Guam; Piarco, Trinidad; and 3 others.
In addition, spatial averaging of anomalies from normals has been
approximated using the mean temperature from the period 1951-1975. For
those few stations where the "normals" were absent, the "normals" were
estimated from data of surrounding stations.
                                                                                
5.4  Processing Changes.  The empirical data on changing global surface air
temperature recently have been revised.  Compared to previous analyses,
rough disturbances in the homogeneity of the observational series at
individual meteorological stations have been eliminated and more adequate
methods for spatial averaging have been used.  Similar revisions have been
carried out in the United Kingdom and the United States (Jones et al. 1985,
1986), in the United States (Hansen and  Lebedeff 1987, 1988), and in
Russia (Vinnikov et al., 1987).  The present archive provides only the
revised data (Vinnikov et al., 1987, 1990).
                                                                                
                                                                                
6.  QUALITY ASSESSMENT                                                          
                                                                                
6.1  Data Validation by Producer.  All the data used have been thoroughly
checked for homogeneity of observational series, representativeness, and
presence of random errors.  The inferences about series homogeneity and
proposals for their correction from Jones, et al. (1985, 1986) have been
also taken into account.
                                                                                
6.2  Confidence Level/Accuracy Judgment.  The estimates obtained with the
monthly resolution can be compared with those from Jones et al., (1986).
The standard deviations, Sigma, linear trend coefficients Beta, correlation
coefficients, Rho, and the mean square values of closure of comparison,
Delta, were compared.  Comparison of mean monthly values of surface air
temperature show a satisfactory agreement of the estimates for both
hemispheres but do not allow us to determine which estimate is more
accurate (Vinnikov et al., 1990).  The three independent estimates are
available for the mean annual surface air temperature.  The first and
second agree well with those from Hansen and Lebedeff (1987, 1988).  The
observed agreement between the series is completely satisfactory.  The
results of estimating the trends confirm the conclusion that modern climate
warming is a global reality.
                                                                                
6.3  Usage Guidance.  The Russian studies, as opposed to others, are based
on the statistically optimum methods for spatial averaging of
meteorological fields developed first by Gandin (1965) and Kagan (1979).
These methods are most effective when information is scarce. Therefore, the
statistically optimum technique provides a sufficiently accurate spatial
averaging procedure when using data from a limited number of stations,
smaller than used by other research groups.  These data are designed for
large-scale temperature change studies.
                                                                                
                                                                                
