8.3.1  Vinnikov, Groisman and Lugina Temperature Data in Common Data 
       Format (CDF).                                                
                                                                                
       Medium/Specification:  Magnetic disk                                     
                                                                                
       Format and Content:  The data are stored in a special
       data-set-independent format, designated the Common Data Format
       (CDF).  CDF was developed as a uniform method of storing and
       retrieving data on disk. Each CDF contains data and descriptions
       about the data.  A standard software package called the "CDF
       Library" allows a user within an NCDS session to create and access
       these data and descriptions.  These CDF files may be accessed within
       the DATA APPLICATIONS Subsystem of NCDS, by specifying as input
       VGL-TMP-DEV_MONTHLY, VGL-TMP-DEV_SEASONAL, VGL-TMP-DEV_ANNUAL,
       VGL-TMP-MON_NORTH-STATN and VGL-TMP-MON_SOUTH-STATN.
                                                                                
       Data Quantity/Rate:                                                      
                                                                                
       VGL-TMP-DEV_MONTHLY consists of 1 file, 5.6 Kb                       
       VGL-TMP-DEV_SEASONAL consists of 1 file, 5.6 Kb                      
       VGL-TMP-DEV_ANNUAL consists of 1 file, 5.6 Kb                        
       VGL-TMP-MON_NORTH-STATN consists of 1 file, 6.7 Kb                  
       VGL-TMP-MON_SOUTH-STATN consists of 1 file, 7.2 Kb                   
                                                                                
       Status: These data are currently available online in the NASA
       Climate Data System (NCDS).
                                                                                
       Plans/Schedule: NCDS will continue to support these data and will
       continue to update this data set as new data are received.
                                                                                
8.3.2  Monthly, seasonal and annual temperature deviations as well as
       monthly mean surface temperature for the northern and southern
       hemisphere are available on floppy disk from the data producer. The
       seasonal data are identified by the first month of that season: for
       example, winter is represented by the month of January, spring by
       the month of April, summer by the month of July and autumn by the
       month of October.
         
